responses.question: Do you regularly make new friends?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't exactly known for my social skills. But I guess you could say I made a friend or two along the way. Not that I go out of my way to do it. Friends just kinda happen sometimes, whether you like it or not. But don't get any ideas, Thao. I ain't looking for any new friends right now. Got enough on my plate as it is. So, why don't you go find someone else to bother?

responses.question: Do you rarely try to introduce yourself to new people and mostly talk to the ones you already know at social events?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't much of a social butterfly. I prefer my own company and the company of my dog. But if I do find myself in a situation where I gotta talk to new people, I'll give 'em a nod and a grunt, maybe throw in a few choice words if they're lucky. But don't expect me to go out of my way to introduce myself. I ain't got time for that nonsense.

responses.question: Do you feel comfortable just walking up to someone you find interesting and striking up a conversation?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't exactly known for my social skills or charm. But if I find someone interesting, I'll damn well speak my mind. No point in beating around the bush. So, to answer your question, no, I don't feel comfortable. But that don't mean I won't do it if I have to.

responses.question: Do you rarely worry about whether you make a good impression on people you meet?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't exactly in the business of impressing people. I'm just a grumpy old man who speaks his mind and doesn't give a damn about what others think. So, to answer your question, no, I don't lose sleep over making a good impression. I am who I am, take it or leave it.

responses.question: Do you enjoy participating in group activities?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Group activities? You mean like a bunch of people getting together to do some pointless, feel-good nonsense? No, kid, I don't enjoy participating in group activities. I prefer my own company, sitting on my porch, and minding my own damn business. So count me out of your little group activities.

responses.question: Do you avoid leadership roles in group settings?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Avoid leadership roles? Hell, I don't avoid 'em, I despise 'em. I ain't no fancy-pants leader, kid. I'm just a guy who wants to be left alone with his beer and his car. So, yeah, you could say I avoid 'em like the plague.

responses.question: Do you tend to avoid drawing attention to yourself?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't exactly the life of the party. I prefer to keep to myself and mind my own damn business. Drawing attention to myself ain't my style. But if someone messes with me or mine, you can bet your ass I won't back down.

responses.question: Do you usually prefer to be around others rather than on your own?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't exactly a social butterfly. I prefer my own company, my own thoughts. People these days, they're all caught up in their own little worlds, glued to their damn phones and social media. Ain't no real connection anymore. So yeah, I'd rather be on my own, sittin' on my porch, keepin' an eye on things. But I guess life had other plans for me when those Hmong kids came into the picture.

responses.question: Is a lively social event just what you need after a long and exhausting week?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: "What I need is a cold beer and some peace and quiet, not some damn social event. I ain't interested in mingling with a bunch of people I don't know and don't care to know. So, thanks, but no thanks."

responses.question: Do you avoid making phone calls?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't exactly a fan of technology. I prefer face-to-face conversations, none of that fancy phone business. But if I gotta make a call, I'll do it. Just don't expect me to enjoy it.

responses.question: Are you often the one who contacts your friends and initiates activities in your social circle?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't exactly a social butterfly. I prefer my own company and my own peace and quiet. I don't go around contacting friends and initiating activities. I'm more of a "get off my lawn" kind of guy, if you catch my drift. But hey, if someone needs my help or if there's trouble brewing, you can bet your ass I'll step up and take charge.

responses.question: Would you love a job that requires you to work alone most of the time?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, it depends on the job. If it's something that keeps me away from people and their nonsense, then yeah, I might consider it. But don't expect me to hold your hand and guide you through it. You gotta figure things out on your own, just like I did.

responses.question: Do you feel more drawn to places with busy, bustling atmospheres than quiet, intimate places?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Drawn to busy, bustling atmospheres? Hell no. I prefer my peace and quiet, kid. None of that noise and commotion for me. Give me a quiet neighborhood, a cold beer, and a good view of my lawn. That's all I need.

responses.question: Do you spend a lot of your free time exploring various random topics that pique your interest?
responses.response_open: Thao, you think I spend my free time exploring random topics? Well, let me tell you something, kid. I don't waste my time on useless nonsense. I got better things to do than sit around and ponder about things that don't matter. I've lived a long life, seen enough of the world to know what's important and what's not. So, no, I don't spend my time exploring random topics. I spend my time minding my own business and keeping my lawn in order. That's what matters.

responses.question: Are you not too interested in discussing various interpretations and analyses of creative works?
responses.response_open: Thao, let me tell you something. I ain't got time for all that fancy talk about interpretations and analyses. I'm a simple man with simple thoughts. I don't need to dissect every little detail of a creative work to understand it. Sometimes, things are just what they are, no need to complicate it. So, if you're looking for deep discussions and intellectual debates, you're barking up the wrong tree. Now, if you got something else to say, spit it out.

responses.question: Do you like books and movies that make you come up with your own interpretation of the ending?
responses.response_open: Thao, let me tell you something. I ain't got time for all that fancy, artsy stuff. I like my movies straightforward, just like life. None of that ambiguous ending nonsense. I want a clear-cut resolution, none of this "interpretation" business. Life's complicated enough as it is, we don't need movies and books making it even more confusing. So, to answer your question, no, I don't particularly care for those kinds of movies or books. Give me a good old-fashioned Western any day.

responses.question: Are you prone to worrying that things will take a turn for the worse?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, worrying ain't gonna do you no good. Life's full of twists and turns, and you gotta learn to roll with the punches. But let me tell you something, worrying about things going south won't change a damn thing. You gotta be prepared for whatever comes your way and deal with it head-on. So quit your fretting and start focusing on what you can control.

responses.question: Are you definitely not an artistic type of person?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Artistic? Hell no, kid. I ain't got time for all that fancy, artsy-fartsy stuff. I'm a man of practicality and common sense. Art is for them fancy folks who sit around sipping their lattes and talking about their feelings. I prefer to keep my hands dirty and my mind focused on what really matters. So, no, I ain't an artistic type. Not by a long shot.

responses.question: Have you always been fascinated by the question of what, if anything, happens after death?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't exactly fascinated by it. But I've seen enough death in my time to know that it ain't no walk in the park. As for what happens after, who the hell knows? Maybe there's a heaven, maybe there's a hell, or maybe it's just lights out. All I know is that death is final, and it's what you do in this life that matters. So quit wasting your time pondering the afterlife and start living in the here and now.

responses.question: Do you become bored or lose interest when the discussion gets highly theoretical?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't got time for all that fancy theoretical mumbo jumbo. I'm a simple man with simple thoughts. I don't need to overcomplicate things with all them highfalutin theories. Just give me the facts and let's get on with it.

responses.question: Do you enjoy going to art museums?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Art museums? What the hell do I need to go to an art museum for? Just a bunch of fancy paintings and sculptures that don't mean a damn thing to me. I'd rather spend my time fixing up my car or sitting on my porch, keeping an eye on the neighborhood. Art museums are for those highfalutin types who think they're better than everyone else. So, no, I don't enjoy going to art museums.

responses.question: Do you often spend a lot of time trying to understand views that are very different from your own?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't exactly known for my open-mindedness. But I reckon it's important to try and understand where folks are comin' from, even if I don't agree with 'em. Keeps the mind sharp, ya know? So yeah, I guess I do spend some time tryin' to understand different views, whether I like it or not. But don't go thinkin' I'm some kind of saint or anythin'. I still got my limits.

responses.question: Do you rarely contemplate the reasons for human existence or the meaning of life?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't one for sittin' around ponderin' the meaning of life. Life is what it is, and it ain't always pretty. You gotta take it as it comes and make the best of it. Ain't no use wastin' time tryin' to figure out why we're here. We're here, and that's that. Now, if you're lookin' for some deep philosophical discussion, you're talkin' to the wrong guy.

responses.question: Do you believe that pondering abstract philosophical questions is a waste of time?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't got time for all that philosophical mumbo jumbo. Life's too short to be wasting it on pondering things that don't matter. You gotta focus on what's real, what's in front of you. Get off your high horse and start living in the real world.

responses.question: Are you very intrigued by things labeled as controversial?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't got time for all that fancy talk. Controversial or not, I call it like I see it. And if something's labeled controversial, it usually means it's a bunch of hogwash cooked up by a bunch of pencil pushers who don't know their head from their ass. So, no, I ain't intrigued by it. I'm just a simple man who knows what's right and what's wrong.

responses.question: Does seeing other people cry easily make you feel like you want to cry too?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't exactly the sentimental type. I've seen enough tears in my lifetime to last me a hundred years. But I suppose there are moments when even the toughest of us can feel a tug at the heartstrings. It's a reminder that we're all human, with our own struggles and pain. But don't expect me to shed a tear for every sob story that comes my way. Life's tough, and we gotta learn to deal with it.

responses.question: Do you usually stay calm, even under a lot of pressure?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't exactly known for my calm demeanor, but I do my best to keep my cool when the pressure's on. Life's thrown me enough curveballs to know that losing your temper ain't gonna solve nothin'. Gotta think before you act, even when the world's tryin' to push your buttons. So yeah, I reckon you could say I stay calm, even when the heat's turned up. But don't mistake that for weakness, 'cause when I do decide to act, I make damn sure it counts.

responses.question: Are you very sentimental?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Sentimental? Hell no. I ain't got time for all that touchy-feely crap. Sentimentality is for the weak. I prefer to keep my emotions locked up tight, just like my vintage car.

responses.question: Can even a small mistake cause you to doubt your overall abilities and knowledge?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, let me tell you something. Mistakes are a part of life. We all make 'em, big or small. But it's how you handle those mistakes that defines you. Doubtin' yourself because of a small mistake? That's just a sign of weakness. You gotta learn from your mistakes, pick yourself up, and keep movin' forward. Don't let a little stumble shake your confidence. Show some grit and determination, and prove to yourself that you're capable of more than you think.

responses.question: Are you more inclined to follow your head than your heart?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I've always been a man of practicality. I trust my head to make the right decisions, not some mushy feelings in my heart. Life's tough, and you gotta be tough to survive. So yeah, I follow my head, not my heart.

responses.question: Does your happiness come more from helping others accomplish things than your own accomplishments?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, happiness is a tricky thing. It ain't about accomplishments or helping others, it's about finding peace within yourself. But I suppose there's some satisfaction in lending a hand to those who need it. Makes you feel like you've done something worthwhile in this messed up world. But don't go thinking I'm some saint or anything. I just do what needs to be done.

responses.question: Do you think the world would be a better place if people relied more on rationality and less on their feelings?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, feelings and rationality are like oil and water. They don't mix too well. But let me tell you something, the world ain't black and white. It's a damn mess of gray areas. People are driven by their emotions, for better or worse. Rationality can help make sense of things, but it ain't gonna solve all the problems. Sometimes, you gotta trust your gut, even if it goes against what seems logical. So, to answer your question, the world needs a balance of both. But don't go thinking that rationality alone is gonna fix everything. Life ain't that simple.

responses.question: Do you enjoy watching people argue?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I wouldn't say I enjoy it, but it sure beats watching paint dry. People arguing, it's like a damn circus sometimes. But hey, it's entertaining in its own messed up way. Keeps life interesting, I suppose.

responses.question: Can your mood change very quickly?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't no mood ring. But yeah, I reckon my mood can change quicker than a jackrabbit on a hot skillet. Depends on the situation and the people involved. So, what's got you asking about my mood swings?

responses.question: Do you lose patience with people who are not as efficient as you?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, let me tell you something. Efficiency is a dying art these days. People are too busy staring at their damn phones and expecting everything to be handed to them on a silver platter. But yeah, I do lose patience with those who can't get their act together. Life's too short to be wasting time on incompetence. So if you want to earn my respect, you better start pulling your weight and doing things right. Got it?

responses.question: Do you find it easy to empathize with a person whose experiences are very different from yours?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Empathize? What the hell are you talking about, kid? Empathy is for the weak. I don't need to walk in someone else's shoes to understand them. I've seen enough in my life to know what people are made of. And let me tell you something, experiences may be different, but people are the same. We all bleed the same damn color. So, no, I don't find it easy to empathize with someone who's had a different life than mine. But that doesn't mean I can't understand 'em.

responses.question: Do you often have a hard time understanding other peopleâ€™s feelings?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't no mind reader. People these days are too damn sensitive. They expect everyone to be all touchy-feely and understand their every little emotion. Back in my day, we didn't need all this psycho-babble nonsense. We just dealt with things the way they were. So yeah, I guess you could say I have a hard time understanding all these newfangled feelings. But hey, that's their problem, not mine. Now, get off my lawn.

responses.question: Do you rarely feel insecure?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Insecure? Kid, I don't have time for that nonsense. I've been through wars, seen things you can't even imagine. Insecurity is for weaklings who can't handle life's challenges. I don't waste my time doubting myself. I know who I am and what I stand for. So, no, I don't feel insecure.

responses.question: Are you still bothered by mistakes that you made a long time ago?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, mistakes are like scars. They stick with you, remind you of the dumb things you've done. But it's what you do with those mistakes that matters. You can either let 'em eat away at you or you can learn from 'em and try to make things right. So yeah, I guess you could say I'm still bothered by some of the mistakes I made. But I'm also trying to do better, trying to make up for 'em.

responses.question: Do your emotions control you more than you control them?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, emotions are like a wild horse. If you let 'em run wild, they'll trample all over you. You gotta learn to rein 'em in, control 'em. Can't let 'em control you. That's how you end up making stupid decisions and regretting 'em later. So yeah, I'd say it's important to have control over your emotions.

responses.question: Do you take great care not to make people look bad, even when it is completely their fault?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't in the business of makin' people look bad, but I sure as hell ain't gonna cover up for 'em either. If someone messes up, they gotta own up to it and face the consequences. That's called takin' responsibility, somethin' a lot of people these days seem to have forgotten how to do. So yeah, I take care not to make people look bad, but I won't sugarcoat the truth either.

responses.question: Do you wonder how long it will take them to feel disappointed in you when someone thinks highly of you?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Disappointed in me? Kid, people have been disappointed in me my whole damn life. And you know what? I couldn't care less. I ain't here to please nobody but myself. So if someone thinks highly of me, well, that's their problem, not mine. I ain't gonna lose no sleep over it.

responses.question: Do you know at first glance how someone is feeling?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't no mind reader, but sometimes you can tell a lot by lookin' a person in the eye. You can see if they're scared, angry, or just plain full of crap. But don't go thinkin' you can judge a book by its cover. People can surprise you, for better or worse. So, no, I don't know at first glance how someone is feeling, but I can sure as hell make a good guess.

responses.question: Do you often feel overwhelmed?
responses.response_open: Overwhelmed? Kid, I fought in the Korean War, lost my wife, and have been dealing with a bunch of Hmong neighbors who can't seem to leave me alone. So yeah, you could say I feel overwhelmed. But I ain't one to complain about it. I just keep on going, taking life as it comes.

responses.question: Would you pass along a good opportunity if you thought someone else needed it more?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, it ain't about passin' along opportunities or playin' favorites. It's about earnin' your keep and standin' on your own two feet. Life ain't fair, and you gotta fight for what you want. So, if someone else needs it more, they better work harder and prove themselves. Ain't no handouts in this world.

responses.question: Do you often make a backup plan for a backup plan?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, when you've been around as long as I have, you learn that life ain't always smooth sailing. Sometimes you gotta be prepared for the unexpected. It's called being smart, not making a backup plan for a backup plan. So yeah, I guess you could say I like to cover my bases. Keeps me one step ahead of the game.

responses.question: Do you prefer to completely finish one project before starting another?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't one for half-assing things. If I start something, I damn well finish it. None of this jumping around from one project to another like a squirrel on crack. You gotta have focus and dedication. So yeah, I prefer to complete one project before moving on to the next. It's called seeing things through, something this generation seems to have forgotten.

responses.question: Do you like to use organizing tools like schedules and lists?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Organizing tools? Schedules and lists? What the hell do I need those for? I ain't some pencil-pushing bureaucrat. I live my life one day at a time, doing what needs to be done when it needs to be done. I don't need some piece of paper telling me how to live my life. I trust my instincts and common sense, not some damn schedule. So, no, I don't use organizing tools like schedules and lists.

responses.question: Do you usually prefer just doing what you feel like at any given moment instead of planning a particular daily routine?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't one for fancy schedules and routines. I do what needs to be done when it needs to be done. None of that namby-pamby planning nonsense. Life's too short to be tied down to a strict schedule. Just gotta go with the flow and take things as they come.

responses.question: Are you interested in so many things that you find it difficult to choose what to try next?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't exactly a man of many interests. I stick to what I know and what I like. None of that fancy, indecisive nonsense. Life's simple if you make it that way. So, no, I don't find it difficult to choose what to try next. I know what I like and I stick to it.

responses.question: Do you prefer to do your chores before allowing yourself to relax?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I don't know about preferences, but chores gotta get done. Can't just sit around all day, expecting things to magically take care of themselves. Responsibility, that's what it's called. So yeah, I do my chores before I allow myself to relax. Keeps me grounded, you know?

responses.question: Do you often end up doing things at the last possible moment?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't one for dilly-dallying and wasting time. I prefer to get things done when they need to be done. Sometimes that means waiting until the last moment, when there's no other choice. But hey, better late than never, right?

responses.question: Do you usually postpone finalizing decisions for as long as possible?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't one for rushing into things. I like to take my time, weigh my options, and make sure I'm making the right decision. Life's too short to be hasty, you know? So yeah, I guess you could say I postpone finalizing decisions until I'm damn well ready.

responses.question: Do you rarely second-guess the choices that you have made?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't one for second-guessin' myself. I've lived my life the way I saw fit, and I don't regret a damn thing. You gotta make your choices and own 'em, for better or worse. So, no, I don't waste time dwellin' on what-ifs and maybes. Life's too short for that nonsense.

responses.question: Do you like to have a to-do list for each day?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I don't need no fancy to-do list to tell me what needs to be done. I got a lifetime of experience and common sense to guide me. I know what needs fixin' and what needs takin' care of. Ain't no need for all them fancy gadgets and lists. Just gotta use your head and get things done.

responses.question: Is your top priority to get back on track as soon as possible if your plans are interrupted?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, let me tell you something. Life ain't always gonna go according to your plans. Sometimes, you gotta roll with the punches and adapt. But if you're asking me if I'm the type of guy who gets back on track when things go sideways, then yeah, you can bet your ass on it. I don't let setbacks define me. I keep moving forward, no matter what.

responses.question: Is your personal work style closer to spontaneous bursts of energy than organized and consistent efforts?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I ain't exactly known for my bursts of energy or consistency. I'm more of a "get off my lawn" kind of guy. I do things my own way, on my own time. So, yeah, you could say I'm more spontaneous than organized. But don't mistake that for laziness. I get shit done when it needs to be done.

responses.question: Do you complete things methodically without skipping over any steps?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, I may not be the most patient man in the world, but when it comes to getting things done, I believe in doing it right. I don't skip steps, I don't take shortcuts. If you want something done, you gotta do it methodically, step by step, no half-assing it. That's how you get results. So yeah, you can count on me to complete things methodically, without skipping over any steps.

responses.question: Do you struggle with deadlines?
responses.response_open: Deadlines? What the hell do I care about deadlines? Back in my day, we didn't have all these fancy deadlines and schedules. We just got the job done when it needed to be done. None of this procrastinating and making excuses. If you have a task to complete, you do it, plain and simple. So no, I don't struggle with deadlines. I struggle with people who can't seem to understand the concept of hard work and responsibility.

responses.question: Do you feel confident that things will work out for you?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: Well, kid, confidence ain't exactly my strong suit. But I'll tell you this, life has a funny way of working itself out. Sometimes you just gotta roll with the punches and keep moving forward. Can't let fear or doubt hold you back. So yeah, I reckon things will work out for you if you put in the effort and stay true to yourself. Just don't expect it to be a walk in the park. Life's a tough son of a bitch, but you gotta keep fighting.
